Review_Title: Wants to infringe on privacy, but you can prevent it!
Review_Content: First off, seems a very solid home printer. No issues with the device itself. Prints a bit slowly, but the prints are of good quality, fine for at home. Document feeder works fine. Should make my life a lot better!That being said, I am so far from impressed it was delivered not just without a usb to print cable, but with the actual port covered with a sticker suggesting WiFi. Yes, HP, I know you want to harvest my data, but no HP, I will not let you. Be assured you can just use this printer wired without WiFi connection at all. In fact I was extremely pleased that the entire setup process was automated and took me under 5 minutes. I'm a Linux user and am used to printer setup being a right pain in the behind but this was smooth as butter. The printer initialisation time is very short as well, so we'll just turn it on and off as needed instead of keeping it powered on. It has a bit of an annoying LED complaining about not having WiFi access, but if you can turn it on and off this quickly not even that is an issue. Perfect printer for those of us who prefer our hardware offline and privacy friendly, HPs pushiness notwithstanding.
Aggregation_Flag: Style Name: HP DeskJet 4220e with Automatic Document FeederPattern Name: White/Grey

Review_Title: Wastes ink and paper printing stuff it wasn't instructed to print.
Review_Content: I quickly learned to remove unused paper after switching off this printer - otherwise it will somehow magic up stuff to print - pages and pages of it before being stopped.  I gave it the email of my most recent phone bill to print - a single page.  Somehow or other - and I do have an HP desktop as well - this printer managed to discover and print about six closely typed pages of previous phone bills, which I had definitely not instructed it to do!  Before buying this particular model I thought I had established that it did double-sided printing (as my previous HP printer did), but annoyingly it involves putting the plain side back into the printer in order to print on the back.  Amazon's product description was accurate, but unfortunately I had obtained information about this particular HP model from a different supplier whose description said it did two-sided printing automatically, which after purchase I find it certainly does not.I do like the ease of putting in new ink cartridges - vital for people with sight problems.
Aggregation_Flag: Style Name: HP DeskJet 2810ePattern Name: White

Review_Title: No instructions given for printing photos.
Review_Content: My old HP printer would still print black text A4, but I replaced it with this because I need to print photos, mostly 4" x 6" colour prints.  I can find no reference in the instruction book to printing colour photos on it, and there is no indication on the paper input where to place any paper less than A4 size, so I tried a couple of guesses - not a success!  I will return the printer if it does not print colour photos on photo paper as it will be less use than the previous cheapest HP printer.I did NOT find it easy to install.  I got the printer working OK quite quickly but the problems started when trying to connect to my HP printer, which had happily worked in conjunction with this printer's previous model.  I had to resort to a local company to get it installed, which was several days delay due to the Easter holiday, and of course this made my purchase rather less than the bargain it first appeared.
Aggregation_Flag: Style Name: HP DeskJet 2810ePattern Name: White

Review_Content: Quality and performance at an unimaginable price. The print quality is good, clear text and good colors is one of the main things I look for in a printer, with it you can print text as images. It has a Scanner, to be able to photocopy and to store files on the PC or mobile.Ink cartridges, these are affordable, and we add the Instant Ink trial and the HP+ trial months included,Instant Ink and HP+ (5/5): I have been especially impressed by HP's Instant Ink service, which Bring ink cartridges home before they run out. Plus, with the HP+ trial, I get free ink for six months, further reducing costs and ensuring I'll never run out of ink. Value for money (5/5): Considering the print quality, the multifunction functionality, how economical the cartridges are and the benefits of Instant Ink and HP+, this printer offers unbeatable value for money. It's an investment worth every penny. In short, the HP DeskJet 2720e All-in-One Printer is a high-quality device that offers affordable printing without compromising performance. With the added benefits of Instant Ink and HP+, it is an ideal choice for those looking for economy and efficiency in their printing solution. I highly recommend this printer to anyone looking for a high-quality printing experience at an affordable price. Review_Title: Stopped doing even its occasional printing once the return window closed one month after purchase.
Review_Content: I am revising my review after 2 months of this printer not working after the Amazon return date expired (one month after purchase). I have had three HP printers delivered from Amazon since January 2024 and it is only JULY.  This last one was the worst of the lot - spent ages on phoneline to HP who took over my computer and got the printer to print a page after a very long session.  The following morning I tried to print and it was back to the same old problem - it simply does not print.  I have been using printers for 20 years at least and my first one did sterling service for years and years.  The HP from Amazon in January 2023 lasted a year, which I accepted as the minimum reasonable lifespan for a cheap printer.  The series of three HP printers since January 2024 is NOT acceptable.  I no longer drive but this one is going to the dump in my shopping trolley on the bus.  I don't want it anywhere near me any longer - it has wasted hours of my time trying to persuade it to do the job it is supposed to be designed to do but doesn't.  That makes three consecutive HP printers in three months that have had to be returned for exchange or refund.  The guarantee period from HP is one year, but I am yet to find a way to get this guarantee period honoured by the retailer.

Review_Title: It IS possible to use it like a normal printer.
Review_Content: HP kind of desperately wants you to use their app for this printer.  I'm personally not a fan, and don't sit around printing things from my phone.  I use a computer, and I connect a printer to it like you normally would.  I don't print things from my phone.  Ever.However, if you go to the support section of the website for this printer:https://support.hp.com/us-en/drivers/hp-deskjet-2800e-all-in-one-printer-series/model/2101372284You can find an actual driver for this printer.  You have to drill down a bit to "HP DeskJet 2800 series EasyStart Printer Setup Software - Offline Use Only", for the printer driver, and one of the 2 available scanner drivers, "HP Universal Scan - Basic Feature Software and Driver ", or "HP Universal Scan - Full Feature Software and Driver".  Personally, if you don't need the advanced, I recommend sticking with the basic.  Don't worry about the "HP Easy Start" or any of that nonsense.  You WILL need a USB cable, as one is NOT provided with this printer.I don't appreciate HP putting a sticker over the USB port as though something will go wrong if you use it.  It even says in the "Reference Guide", "Do not use USB for setup".  Um, hey HP...are you listening?DON'T COMMAND ME.  That, I do NOT appreciate.  I accept that perhaps you WANT people to use the app, for all the data mining opportunities that provides, but you may SUGGEST it to me.  "We recommend not using the USB for setup."  Or, "We recommend wireless setup instead of USB."  Not, "DO NOT USE USB FOR SETUP."I'm the customer.  That doesn't mean you get to command me, or dictate to me.Ideally?  HP should be 100% NEUTRAL on how you connect your printer.  Why do they care, and what business is it of theirs, if I connect it with a USB cable, with the app, with wifi, with a CAT5 network cable, or with a stinking serial cable.  Just give me the options I want to connect the printer the way I WANT to connect the printer, and leave me ALONE.So for HP to be like...NO, don't you DARE connect this printer via USB.  YOU WILL DO AS WE SAY.  I don't know where they got that mentality, or who told them that's an OK way to be, but it's not.  I took 1 star away for HP trying to dictate to me how MY printer will be used.  And -1 star for trying to hide other connectivity options to begin with.  What's wrong with you.  Nothing about trying to dictate to the customer is ok.  It wasn't ok 50 years ago, and it's not ok today.So, once you get the drivers downloaded, get your self-supplied USB cable connected to it, and get it hooked up, it's pretty painless and works like a printer should work.  The only drawback now, being ink volume and cost, which is pretty high with this printer.  High enough that they want you to subscribe for it like it's medicine.  And I'm sure the push notifications about your printer being low on ink and won't you please order some more direct from HP at the highest possible price will begin shortly thereafter.  Nah, I'll pass.As far as being a basic little AIO printer goes, it gets the job done without too much difficulty.  Print quality is ok for the price, and scan quality is actually pretty good.  But make sure you calculate your ink costs before committing to this printer.My only problem with it (and it's a big problem) is HP's attempt now to strong-arm you into using their app instead of just...I dunno...plugging it in like we used to.  It sure would be nice to see them stop being abusive to their customers, both in their "app encouragement policies" as well as their "ink cost" policy.  If you actually sit around and do word processing on your phone, and need an app for everything, this may be the printer for you.  If not, you may want to question HP's current direction.

Review_Title: An odyssey to connect it via WIFI
Review_Content: When the printer is in operation, it offers excellent performance. The quality of the prints, scans and copies is remarkable, although it seems to use a lot of ink (I used 2 black cartridges in 3 weeks, printing only about 100 pages). However, the real disappointment is the HP "Smart" configuration software. I couldn't get it to work over Wi-Fi and every time I tried to reinstall the printer, different problems arose. I couldn't even configure it using a USB cable. Finally, I went back and installed HP's previous setup software, HP Printer Assistant, and managed to get it working with a USB cable. But why buy a printer with Wi-Fi if it needs a cable to work? Also, you can't set it up with any of the apps without a USB cable. Both applications require the use of a cable because the printer does not have a touch screen, and this information is not mentioned on the outside of the box, forcing me to make a second trip to purchase a cable. Since HP knows that a cable is needed to set it up, they should include one with the printer or at least clearly warn about this need. Bottom line: a great printer if you don't need to use it over Wi-Fi, but the setup software leaves a lot to be desired.
Aggregation_Flag: Diseño: NuevaNombre de estilo: Con alimentador automático
Orginal_Review: Cuando la impresora está en funcionamiento, ofrece un rendimiento excelente. La calidad de las impresiones, escaneos y copias es destacable, aunque parece gastar bastante tinta (utilicé 2 cartuchos negros en 3 semanas, imprimiendo apenas unas 100 páginas). Sin embargo, la verdadera decepción es el software de configuración HP "Smart". No logré hacerlo funcionar por Wi-Fi y cada vez que intentaba reinstalar la impresora, surgían problemas diferentes. Ni siquiera pude configurarla utilizando un cable USB. Finalmente, retrocedí e instalé el software de configuración anterior de HP, el Asistente de Impresoras de HP, y logré hacerla funcionar con un cable USB. Pero ¿por qué comprar una impresora con Wi-Fi si necesita un cable para funcionar? Además, no puedes configurarla con ninguna de las aplicaciones sin un cable USB. Ambas aplicaciones requieren el uso de un cable porque la impresora no tiene pantalla táctil, y esta información no se menciona en el exterior de la caja, lo que me obligó a hacer un segundo viaje para comprar un cable. Dado que HP sabe que se necesita un cable para configurarla, deberían incluir uno con la impresora o al menos advertir claramente sobre esta necesidad. En resumen: una impresora excelente si no necesitas usarla por Wi-Fi, pero el software de configuración deja mucho que desear.

Review_Title: Solid Home Printer But Very Slow If Printing Images So If You Must Buy It Then Wait For A Sale
Review_Content: The HP DeskJet 2810e is a good all-in-one printer for basic home use. Setting it up was a relatively simple process and the Wi-Fi connection has been reliable so far. The print quality is pretty decent, especially for text documents and printing sewing patterns. I was also happy with the included 3 months of Instant Ink, which helped me avoid running out of ink right away.However, there are a couple of things to keep in mind. The printing speed isn't the fastest, so it's not ideal for high-volume printing jobs. This is especially true when printing pictures, even really basic ones and even when you're printing one image. My mother still has her old dot matrix printer from the mid 1980s and while it doesn't print in colour the black and white images it produces still print faster than this HP printer doing the same job!Also the paper tray is a bit on the small side, so you'll need to refill it more often if you print a lot. I think this holds 60 pages.Overall, I'd give the HP DeskJet 2810e 4 out of 5 stars. It's a good value for the (sale) price, and it's easy to use. Just be aware of the limitations if you need a printer for heavy-duty tasks and pictures. I bought this when it was in a sale and paid under £40 which is about right. I wouldn't pay full price.

Review_Title: HP Printers are reliable however Instant Ink is a double edged sword
Review_Content: This is a decent basic entry level printer. It is nothing special, a very basic multi-function printer/scanner. This would be best suited to someone who uses a printer infrequently. It is a decent printer; however it has some shortcomings. It can only hold 60 sheets of paper before needing to add more. This is perfect for a home user that doesn't print or copy documents too often, however printing large documents or frequent use would become annoying. HP printers are reliable however, they can be frustrating to setup initially via Wi-Fi. Support can also be challenging to get through HP. I would HIGHLY recommend staying far away from the HP Instant Ink service. This printer is advertised as including 3 months of free ink. This is true but it comes at a huge cost. The service will limit the number of pages that your printer can print based on your monthly subscription level. You will also need to pay the monthly subscription fee regardless of whether you use the printer or not. If the subscription is canceled the cartridges will not work with the printer anymore even if they are full. The instant ink service is pretty much like paying a monthly fee for access to your own printer. It is not required to sign up for this service, you can opt out during the setup of your printer. It is much easier to just go to the store and buy your own ink cartridges when they run low. Overall if you need a very cheap multifunction printer, this isn’t a bad option if you opt out of HP Instant Ink.
Seeding_Flag: Vine Customer Review of Free Product
Aggregation_Flag: Style: New Version

Review_Content: This is a nice basic printer for the money and HP has been making the DeskJet series for many years using Ink Jet technology.  There are few moving parts and these are made mostly of plastic so they are inexpensive.  You would think that after so many years they would have reached perfection - but it seems like they have stalled out and the features are not much different than they were 5-10 years ago - but they are still unpredictable in connecting to your home network - sometimes it works perfectly and sometimes it takes you a while with tech support.Overall the print quality is OK and the print speed is OK for light home use.  In my experience, Ink Jet printers must be used regularly in order to keep working and avoid drying out.If you opt in to the HP+ app and their printer Ink supply this printer will no longer work with any third party recycled or remanufactured cartridges - if it is not HP (at 2-3 times the price), your printer will no longer work period.  The alternative is to carefully opt out of their service and just install the basic drivers that are available.  I say carefully because the HP Install and upgrade apps are relentless in trying to force you into a permanent relationship.  This is clearly disclosed in the listing and documentation - but be advised they are much more aggressive in enforcement with this and other "e" models.

Review_Title: Excellent printer hardware but outrageous HP's ink subscription scam!
Review_Content: Overall, this compact inkjet printer proves to be a great choice, especially considering its category compared to laser printers. I needed something compact, all-in-one, and cheap for occasional personal printing needs, and this printer fits the bill perfectly. It has a built-in scanner on the top, but no ADF (there is a higher model of this printer with ADF if you require it). No paper tray either, pages are inserted vertically in a slot on the back of the printer. Also, there is no memory card slot in the printer to store scanned images, all scans have to be transmitted and stored on the connected device. While it lacks scanning software out of the box, I easily remedied this by using Microsoft's free scan software, which performs perfectly with this scanner. The printer operates solely via Wi-Fi, there is no Ethernet or USB port at all. Setting up the printer is relatively straightforward. I initiated the setup on my computer, then installed the app on my phone, seamlessly coordinating between both devices. I was prompted to sign up for an instant ink plan during setup, but I declined due to the subscription charges per printed page, which is ridiculous. Without enrolling in the instant ink or HP+ program, the printer comes with a one-year warranty, extendable to two years with HP+. Compared to my old Epson printer, this one has faster printing speeds and quieter operation. The print quality meets my needs, although I primarily use it for personal, non-business-related printing. The scanner produces crisp images, and I can even push its resolution to 1200 dpi! While it includes two ink cartridges, it is only sufficient for test pages, which might be intentional, forcing you to order new ink cartridges almost immediately. This is really annoying that HP persistently attempts to enroll you in their ink subscription program. While I like the printer hardware, this HP's subscription program is a real rip-off. The plans charge you for printing, yes, they charge you per page on your own paper that you've already paid for. So, for 10 pages a month it's $1.49, and it goes up from there with 50 pages $4.99, 100 pages (they recommend) $6.99, 300 pages $13.99 and finally 700 pages $27.99. And if you print more than the plan allows, they will charge you additional fees!!! This is outrageous! But wait for even more, HP is now forcing you to use only their super-expensive ink with so-called “dynamic security” feature. All it does is block any non-OEM ink you might try to use in the printer. Jeez, it's as if my car's manufacturer would be charging me per mile I drive and was trying to stop me from using any gasoline, forcing me to only fill up my tank with their brand gas. I can't believe how greedy HP has become these days. My advice - do not subscribe for any ink, buy 3rd party compatible and cheap ink, and most importantly, never update firmware that will block you from using cheap ink. Overall, it's a nice printer, but greedy and dishonest HP tactics ruin the whole user experience for me.Bottom line:This compact HP inkjet printer is ideal for personal use but lacks some features like an automatic document feeder and a memory card slot. Setup is easy via Wi-Fi, but there is no Ethernet or USB connection. Printing and scanning quality are great. But beware of HP's pushy ink subscription program. HP's aggressive tactics and expensive ink are major drawbacks. Opt for cheap third-party ink and avoid firmware updates that block non-OEM ink to maximize value. While printer hardware is great, this ink subscription scam does not let me give it more than 3 stars rating.Pros:1. Compact and all-in-one design.2. Easy setup via Wi-Fi.3. Good printing and scanning quality.4. Fast printing speeds and quiet operation.5. Fairly cheap for its capabilities.Cons:1. Pushy ink subscription program from HP.2. Expensive OEM ink cartridges.3. Firmware updates block third-party ink.4. No Ethernet or USB ports.5. No automatic document feeder.6. No memory card slot for scans.

Review_Content: I ordered this printer for my neighbor, if only I hadn't done that. I made the poor woman miserable because the damn thing wasn't ready to print. From the beginning: when her husband was still alive, they had the previous model with the ink cartridge subscription (no PC) and always printed pictures from their cell phone via their WiFi without any problems. Then her husband died and she canceled the subscription...a few days later the printer stopped printing, the orange information light was on and nothing came except meaningless status reports. My neighbor said the printer was defective, threw it away with the remaining new print cartridges and asked me to order the replacement model for her. (The old printer is still in the basement) The new printer arrives, after several attempts (I could write a whole drama about that alone) it declares itself ready to print. My neighbor printed some documents and pictures for two days, but she didn't expect HP's revenge. Since she hadn't taken out a new print cartridge subscription, the orange information light came on on the third day and printing stopped. The motto was to send it back, but that also went wrong because the return slip that Amazon provided did not contain a known sender. We could have sent the thing with DHL at our own expense, but we didn't want to, and every time I talked to my neighbor about what to do next, she burst into tears. She just couldn't see the stupid printer anymore, wasted the €60, gave it to a friend for her computer group and that was it :((

Ich habe die arme Frau damit totunglücklich gemacht, weil das verdammte Ding nicht zum Drucken bereit war. Von vorn: als ihr Ehemann noch lebte hatten sie das Vorgängermodell mit dem Tintenpatronenabo (kein PC) und immer problemlos Bilder vom Handy über ihr Wlan gedruckt. Dann starb ihr Mann und sie kündigte das Abo...einige Tage später druckte der Drucker nicht mehr, die orangene Infoleuchte war an und außer nichtssagenden Statusberichten kam nichts mehr. Meine Nachbarin meinte, der Drucker sei defekt, entsorgte ihn mit den restlichen, neuen Druckpatronen und bat mich das Nachfolgemodell für sie zu bestellen. (Der alte Drucker steht noch im Kellergang) Der neue Drucker kommt, nach etlichen Versuchen (allein darüber könnte ich ein ganzes Drama schreiben)  erklärt er sich zum Drucken bereit. Meine Nachbarin druckt zwei Tage lang einige Dokumente und Bilder aus, aber sie hatte nicht mit der Rache von HP gerechnet. Da sie kein neues Abo für Druckpatronen abgeschlossen hatte, ging am dritten Tag die orangene Infolampe an und aus war es mit dem Drucken. Zurücksenden war die Devise, aber auch das ging schief, denn der Rücksendeschein den Amazon lieferte enthielt keinen bekannten Versender. Wir hätten das Ding auf eigene Kosten mit DHL schicken können, wollten wir aber nicht, und jedes Mal wenn ich mit meiner Nachbarin über das weitere Vorgehen sprach, brach sie in Tränen aus. Sie konnte den blöden Drucker einfach nicht mehr sehen, setzte die 60€ in den Sand, gab das Ding einer Freundin für deren Computergruppe mit und das wars :((

Review_Title: Fantastic small footprint WiFi printer for the home office
Review_Content: I have been using HP printers for decades. I have a 9000 series at the house now and it's a big printer so I like that this has a smaller footprint.  I also like that it has the same features as the larger model: flatbed scanner, sheet fed scanner, WiFi and is an all in one printer with great quality.  The only thing it doesnt have that I like about my other printer is the ethernet interface.  Is ethernet worth 3x the price?  For most people, probably not.  I have been an HP all in one user for over a decade with the subscription service for ink and that is a game changer.  This was quick to set up, uses the same app to control, I can WiFi print from my phones, tablets and couch and don't have to worry about it taking up a massive amount of space so to me this is a huge win.  Well worth the price for any home or home office user...and a slam dunk for college kids.

Review_Title: HP DeskJet Printer: Great Value, Watch Out for Ink!
Review_Content: This HP DeskJet is a decent, budget-friendly all-in-one printer for occasional use. Here's what you need to know:Pros:- Compact and affordable: Perfect for personal printing needs with its small size and low price tag.- Good quality: Prints and scans well for home use.- Easy to use: Straightforward Wi-Fi setup although slower than some more traditional printer setups.- Fast and quiet: Prints quickly and operates quietly.Cons:- Limited paper tray: Can only hold 60 sheets of paper at a time.- HP Instant Ink: Avoid this subscription service with hidden fees and limited printing unless you fully understand it.- Ink cartridges: HP ink is expensive, and they have done all they can to block you from buying buying compatible non-HP cartridges.- Limited features: No automatic document feeder, memory card slot, Ethernet port, or USB port.- Limited support for non-WiFi/non-SmartPrinter configuration.Overall:This HP DeskJet is a good option for basic printing and scanning needs, especially if you find a deal. Just be aware of the limitations and HP's pushy ink subscription service. By using compatible ink and avoiding HP Instant Ink, you can get a great value out of this printer.

Review_Content: Oh boy. HP will never get 5 stars because the "3 months of free ink" is only true if you sign up for Instant Ink. Now, that's perfectly fine! I knew that! What I didn't know was that signing up for Instant Ink means that you must enable HP+. HP+ lets HP remotely update your device's firmware and potentially limit your account or decide which inks you can and cannot use. Since I did not want this, obviously I could not get the free ink offer. This also disables some of the "smart" features. Luckily I don't really need them, but this feels like a bait and switch to me.If you refuse and do NOT sign your printer up with HP, you should be able to refill your cartridges by following guides online. I did indeed download the HP Smart software and have used the scanning feature so far. It works well, I like the quality of the saved PDFs. It's my first modern printer/scanner and I'm happy with it so far. Will update my review once I get some paper and again when I refill the ink for the first time.

Review_Title: Specs say Monthly Duty Cycle is "Up to 1000 pages." Each HP 67 ink cartridge yields 100 -120 pages.
Review_Content: Review for HP DeskJet 4255e Wireless All-in-One Color Inkjet Printer, Scanner, Copier, Best-for-Home.This is a very light duty printer.  HP specs recommend only printing 100 to 300 pages per month.  That is only 3 to 10 pages per day.  This means that you don't want to print up longer documents on this printer, or you risk overheating it.  This printer is made for very occasional printing.It uses HP 67 ink cartridges.  The black cartridge yields about 120 pages while the color cartridge yields about 100 pages.The all in one aspect is nice.  However, it only has a 60 sheet paper tray, which is in line with this printer not being one that you use much.You can only make up to 9 copies at a time.This copier's specs also state that HP "uses dynamic security measures to block cartridges using modified or non-HP circuitry. Periodic firmware updates will maintain the effectiveness of these measures and block cartridges that previously worked."  This means that you can only use HP cartridges in this printer.The printer scans at a decent resolution (1200 x 1200 dpi).  It will print at 300 dpi.Overall, this printer's specs are the lowest that I have every owned.  And because of that, I am not happy with this printer.  At this price point, the specs should be higher.

Review_Content: In recent years I have used HP printers more often in small businesses as well as privately. The printer "HP DeskJet 2820e" should be inexpensive and only be enough for a few pages a year. Unfortunately, despite having IT training, I couldn't persuade the printer to print a single page. A total of 25 problem solutions (network, Windows operating system, printer itself) were carried out in a time-consuming manner. No chance. I still have other HP models from the mainstream class running (2X HP OfficeJet Pro 8022e), and they all had technical problems before the warranty period expired and had to be sent in. Due to the poor quality, I will stay away from HP. In my opinion, the printers, even in private use, are not reliable. You have to live with the software. The compulsory registration is a nuisance. Anyone who has to register an HP account in order to be able to use the relevant functions in the software (e.g. scanning) may have to wait 6 hours until a confirmation email is sent to their own email address. The setup process can only be continued by clicking on the confirmation link. If you need to set up a printer for an acquaintance or friend, then they can arrive again the next day. After using several HP models, I cannot recommend using it. The printers I had had poor durability.

Leider konnte ich den Drucker, trotz IT-Ausbildung, nicht zu einer einzigen Seite des Druckens überreden. Insgesamt 25 Problemlösungen (Netzwerk, Windows Betriebssystem, Drucker an sich) wurden zeitaufwendig durchgeführt. Keine Chance.Ich habe noch andere Modelle von HP aus der Mainstream Klasse am laufen (2X HP OfficeJet Pro 8022e), und diese haben vor Ablauf der Gewährleistungsfrist allesamt technische Probleme und mussten eingeschickt werden. Aufgrund der schlechten Qualität, werde ich von HP Abstand nehmen. Meines Erachtens sind die Drucker, selbst im Privatbereich, nicht zuverlässigMit der Software muss man leben. Wer ein HP Konto anmelden muss, um die in der Software relevanten Funktionen bedienen zu können (z.B. scannen), muss mitunter 6 Stunden warten, bis eine Bestätigungsmail auf die eigene E-Mail Adresse gesendet wird. Erst mit Klick auf dem Bestätigungslink kann der Einrichtungsprozess fortgesetzt werden. Review_Title: Effortless Printing: A Reliable Companion for Every Task
Review_Content: After much research and contemplation, I decided to take the plunge and invest in this printer/scanner, and I couldn't be happier with my decision. Setting it up was surprisingly simple, despite my initial concerns about its wireless functionality. Like many others, I've had my fair share of connectivity issues in the past, but this device has been rock-solid in terms of communication with my devices.One of the features that really won me over is its versatility. As someone who enjoys cross-stitching, being able to easily print PDF patterns directly from my phone is a game-changer. Additionally, the scanning function has proven to be incredibly useful for digitizing patterns from magazines without damaging them.I've also been impressed by the efficiency of the ink usage, especially when using the XL cartridges and printing in 'draft' mode. Despite printing numerous pages, the ink levels have held up admirably. And the HP Smart app has made the entire printing process a breeze.Reading about the unfortunate experiences of others, particularly the one who had to deal with a defective unit, made me a bit wary. However, I'm pleased to report that my experience with this printer has been nothing short of fantastic. It's reliable, efficient, and offers exceptional value for the price.In conclusion, if you're in the market for a reliable printer/scanner that won't break the bank, I wholeheartedly recommend giving this one a try. It's been a game-changer for me, and I couldn't be more satisfied with my purchase.

Aggregation_Flag: Style: New Version

Review_Title: Had It a While and So Far, So Good - With One or Two Annoyances
Review_Content: Got this a couple of weeks ago, but wanted to have some time with it to see how it does. Right now, the price is just under $70, which is a lot of bang (features) for the buck. It has all the stuff I'm used to from my old HP printer: scan, send to computer, copy, print. But also adds something I really have been wanting: print from smart phone.That's a big plus, because these days, we do a lot on our phones, and up until now, it meant emailing anything to print to a desktop computer, then going to there, opening the email. saving the image to print, then printing it. A lot of extra steps that are now eliminated.I do wish these printers would go back to using separate color ink cartridges so I don't throw away good ink just because one color runs out first. I guess the idea is to both cut costs and sell me more ink cartridges. Clearly these printers are not a big money maker at this price point, so the profits come from selling replacement ink. I get it.This does come with an offer for free ink for three months. But after that, if you don't tell them you want out of the program, you get billed each month. Unless you use a LOT of ink, I'm not sure that's a good bargain. Personally, I'll pass on that. I've also had not big problems with refiled cartridges for my old HP printer I've gotten from Amazon, and those save me money.As far as print and scan quality, it is as good if not better than my old HP printer. I've not had any issues with paper feeding or jams. And I mostly use copy paper, which is more or less the cheapest paper you can get. If it is happy with that, it should be happy with any paper.One other thing I wish they had not changed from my old printer is the paper feed on top back. I prefer having paper stored in a drawer underneath. With the feeder sticking up, the printer had to be moved further out. In essence, it makes the footprint bigger than what the dimensions quote, so it eats up more space on my desk than I expected in order to give room for the slanted feed sticking out the back side.Other than that, its seems to be a good printer, doing as good a job as my old one, but with the big added advantage of printing easily from my phone. Setup wit the network and phone app was easy and didn't take long. It worked the first time - more than I can say for some other devices I have that were a pain to connect.But even so, I'm giving four stars, not five. That paper feed tray is not ideal, and forced me to move the printer further forward than expected. So I deducted a star. And I still wish they would go back to separate inks for each color rather than waste a lot of ink.

Review_Content: Getting this printer to replace an aging (10-year old plus) Brother printer ended up being the right decision. Unboxing and setup are quick and easy, with the software walking you through the process. Adding it to my iPhone was just as easy, and it found the printer immediately after downloading and opening the app.  I ended up having the device unpacked and set up to work with two devices within 15 minutes, including printing and scanning the alignment sheet.Overall quality is very good, and I won't hesitate to use this for everyday printing for both home and work. The scanner also works well, and I had no issue scanning 10 sheets using the included 35-sheet document feeder.  I don't print enough consistent volume to subscribe to the HP Instant Ink program, and the constat reminders in the app gets a little annoying even after declining. I do wish the 60-sheet paper tray were on the bottom rather than sticking out the back, but that's a minor issue that doesn't negatively affect its performance, just a personal preference.All in all, this is a good printer and good value that should last a long time with proper care and maintenance.

Review_Title: Connectivity Issues - Print via Hotspot Option
Review_Content: First off this is a major pain to set up (connect). Be aware it has specific requirements for initial set up - 2.4 internet and a desktop/laptop can be hard to find the correct combination. It cannot be set up on 5G. However, it says once it is set up via 2.4 then 5G can be used to print. I cannot confirm this. Nowhere did it say any of this in the description. I was only made aware via paperwork provided in the box. It took me 4 different attempts/locations/combinations of the above to get mine to work...It does not say Hotspots can be used to print and there are no instructions on how to do so. I had to contact HP Support. Even then they tried to tell me I needed Wifi. You do not. You can print via your Hotspot, if you made it through the hair-pulling process of initial setup. The printer has to be in WIFI-DIRECT mode to print via Hotspot. Press Info & Resume buttons at the same time and an icon of a printer with a phone beside it will appear. Good luck!

Great find all around!

Our 10+ year-old HP printer is starting to sound like a scary monster when you print something so it was time to replace. Our old printer had lots of bells and whistles. I was looking for a printer that was wireless and could still scan & copy. I found this HP 4255 and figured we could give it a shot.Setup was easy and took more time to get it out of the box and all the tape off. Since we were moving from an HP, we already had the necessary apps installed on our phones and computers.I prefer to connect devices that don't move around to my ethernet network and not WIFI. Our old printer did have an ethernet port and this one doesn't.Print quality seems to be much improved over our old printer. We were a little disappointed that it does not print front-back automatically. Although the printer does print one side of the page and pauses for to reload the paper manually to print the other side.This printer also lacks USB & media ports. This was handy if I needed to printer several documents or photos. Sending them over the network becomes tedious and slow.Overall, a little more basic than we hoped but gets the job down.

Review_Content: It hasn't given me anything but problems and I've only had it for two days. The initial installation can only be done with the HP Smart app. They ask you if you want to register for HP+ to get I don't know what advantages (to have your personal data, basically), then if you want to sign up for an HP account (without the +) to be able to “enjoy” a subscription to Instant Ink. Not to everything, thank you. And so far so good. The problems begin when you realize that you can only print or scan from the app if you have an HP account. If not, you have to find a life. From the PC, Windows has no problem printing and scanning without the app. From iPhone you use AirPrint (to scan I was only able to do it via the web, and it was not easy) and from Android I downloaded the Morpia printing and scanner apps (free and without having to create an account or provide any information). Another big problem What I found is that you can basically only print using wifi. It does not work with cable and with Wi-Fi Direct you need a code that can only be obtained by printing a sheet. The code changes every time you connect and is only valid for 120 seconds. Come on, you're losing the little ink that the cartridges have printing this little number. A complete scam. More problems. The day after installing the printer, in the middle of printing a whopping 2 sheets (!!) the printer disconnected from the network. According to Windows the error was “driver not available”. According to the printer and after printing a 3-page report (what a nice scam to waste ink on useless information) everything was perfect. To reconnect it I had to reinstall the HP app (I deleted it as soon as I finished the initial configuration... what a delusion I was, to think that everything was going to work well) and configure everything again. A real shame and waste of time. The print quality is average, but it is to be expected for the price and being a low-end printer. The printer is now back in Amazon warehouses and I will not buy an HP again in my life.
Aggregation_Flag: Diseño: NuevaNombre de estilo: Sin alimentador automático
Orginal_Review: No me ha dado nada más que problemas y eso que la he tenido solo dos días.La instalación inicial solo se puede hacer con la app HP Smart. Te preguntan que si quieres registrarte en HP+ para conseguir no sé que ventajas (para tener tus datos personales, básicamente), luego que si quieres hacerte cuenta en HP (sin el +) para poder “disfrutar” de una subscripción a Instant Ink. No a todo, gracias.Y hasta ahí bien. Los problemas empiezan cuando te das cuenta de que para imprimir o escanear desde la app solo lo puedes hacer si tienes cuenta HP. Si no, te tienes que buscar la vida. Desde el PC, Windows no tiene problema para imprimir y escanear sin la app. Desde iPhone usas AirPrint (para escanear solo fui capaz de hacerlo vía web, y no fue fácil) y desde Android yo descargué las apps de impresión y scanner de Morpia (gratuitas y sin tener que crear cuenta ni dar ninguna información).Otro gran problema que me encontré es que básicamente solo puedes imprimir usando wifi. No funciona con cable y con Wi-Fi Direct necesitas un código que solo se consigue imprimiendo una hoja. El dichoso código cambia cada vez que te conectas y solo es válido durante 120 segundos. Vamos, que se te va la poca tinta que tienen los cartuchos imprimiendo este numerito. Un timo en toda regla.Más problemas. El día después de instalar la impresora, a mitad de una impresión de la enorme cantidad de 2 hojas (!!) la impresora se desconectó de la red. Según Windows el error fue “controlador no disponible”. Según la impresora y después de imprimir un informe de 3 hojas (que bonito timo lo de gastar tinta con información inútil) todo estaba perfecto. Para volver a conectarla tuve que reinstalar la app de HP (la borré tan pronto acabé con la configuración inicial… que ilusa yo, pensar que todo iba a funcionar bien) y volver a configurar todo otra vez. Una auténtica vergüenza y pérdida de tiempo.La calidad de impresión es normalita, pero es de esperar por el precio que tiene y siendo una impresora de gama baja.La impresora está ya de vuelta en los almacenes de Amazon y no vuelvo a comprar una HP en mi vida.

Review_Content: I needed a second printer for my home, and this one was very affordable. Quick and easy fast set up. You need to have HP Smart on your phone and laptop. I signed up for HP+, but made sure to skip the HP Smart Ink program that is giving everyone a headache. The printer connected wirelessly on my Xfinity wifi.
Aggregation_Flag: Style: New Version

Review_Content:
I’ll start with the packaging. This printer came well protected with padding and the entire unit was covered in a plastic wrap – excellent. No hard lifting, the unit easily slipped out of the box. There were a few blue tape pieces to remove and the entire process proved to be intuitive and simple. 

You can setup from a cell phone or from a computer. I wanted to try setting it up from a computer this time. I already had installed the HP Smart app (for my other HP printers) so I just clicked the add new printer button. I also could have gone to the HP web site to install. I highly recommend the HP Smart app since it simplifies the entire process from turning the printer on the first time to alignment to printing your first page. I noticed that when I did my first print, HP Smart had included all the printers I had on my computer in the selection box – very nice to see everything was already integrated. This process included the initial install of cartridges. This was the easiest install I have ever made. You can choose to enroll in HP Ink or not. HP has refined the process to get your WiFi connected to the printer, it spotted the printer right away and was super fast to connect. I was also given the option to update firmware during the initial setup. Tip of the cap to the HP engineers for upgrading this whole process to very few steps. 

Alignment took a few minutes using the alignment sheet which is printed out and placed on the scanning glass. All functions worked nicely for scanning, copying and printing. This printer had an innovative input feed on the back of the printer that held 60 sheets. I found this newer design easier to use when adding more paper and you can see if paper is running low – another tip of the cap to the engineers. 

This is a very solid and functional device, it even includes a document feeder. I have had many printers from many brands, this unit is the best I have seen at such an affordable price-point; I would highly recommend it.

Review_Title: A very good, economical printer for light printing
Review_Content:
Printers have not always been my favorite topic, even as a computer guy I see them as mostly an ends to a means.  Having a great printer is never anything you usually hear anyone say anything about.  I've had a lot of luck with HP through the years and, contrary to what some may think, the HP Ink is really a great value for most of us.  One could argue the economic impact of it but I believe if you value your time, as most of us do, then it's a no-brainer that you should want to use HP Ink.  For those of you who aren't aware, HP Ink is a subscription service that starts at $1.99 a month for light printing, then there are various tiers depending upon how much you print.  I know it doesn't sound very good, but having had it, and used it for several years, I can tell you it's a great program that will save you a lot of time and money.  Be aware that, for this printer, it is a requirement as well.

Setting up the printer was not easy.  However, I believe it was made difficult for me more so due to the fact that I had an older HP printer and had to decommission it on HP Ink before registering the new one.  Do note that you really should look at the instructions before you just scan the barcode and start setting it all up.  Companies are sort of training us to just do it all on our phone but do read the instructions in the box (quick start) and you'll find your time is cut down considerably.  

Prior to receiving this printer I had read some reviews and many reviews seemed to indicate that the actual printouts from this printer were incredibly poor and fuzzy looking.  I did not have this experience, as so far, all of my print outs have been done really well and look startingly good for a printer considered to be a value printer.  I have attached a few pictures for you to see for yourself.  These are all at default printer settings.  

I must also say that I did not have any issues with papers printing and then falling to the floor.  I suspect whomever said this was not aware of how to properly extend the tray branches, which it has one on each side.  Once this is done I've printed multiple pages and none have fell out of the printers casing where it prints to.  

I'm very happy with this printer.  I did have to deduct a star for the sloppy setup, which was made difficult by already having an HP printer, when it should be made easier I think if you already have an HP account.  Once I got that out of the way the printer has been pretty good, without any issues at all and I'm quite happy with how it prints and how the print outs look.  A great economical printer for users who want to spend less time, money and worry about printing.

Review_Content:
The HP 4255e all in one inkjet printer is an allround office/home solution. The printer is very well built and is lightweight. It is white in color with a gray accent. It has a small LCD display and several function buttons. It was very easy to set up using the HPSmart app. It comes with two sets of ink, a color cartridge and a black. This printer can be used via USB, Wi-Fi direct, or it can be connected to a network via Wi-Fi. I was able to install it on my Windows PC without the app and Android OS using the HP smart app. If you want to be able to use all the printer features in Windows OS, you will be required to download the HP Smart app. I was not able to use the scanner without the HP smart app. I tried using it with Windows' own scan app, but the printer didn’t even show up on the list. The windows scan app is very limited. Also, you will not be able to scan using HP's own app unless you create an HP account, which I found troublesome.

There are two ways to scan, using the automatic feeder or the flat glass. The glass supports paper size up to A4 or Letter 8.5x11. With the ADF you can scan legal size documents. It seems that this scanner does not support dual side scan. The scan quality is pretty good. When scanning you have to manually select the source as the printer is not smart enough to figure where the document is located. Scanning quality is good and goes up to 1200 dpi with the lowest at 300. The scanning speed was fast and very quiet. If you choose a higher quality scan be aware that will affect the scanning speed. At 1200 dpi it took several minutes.

Printing is a breeze and it does it really fast with good quality. This printer holds up to 60 sheets of paper on the paper tray and 35 on the ADF tray. The control panel is a small LCD screen and several buttons. It only displays several settings like paper count, brightness and other common features. On the screen you also have an ink level indicator as well. This printer comes with a 30 day trial for ink refills. When the printer detects you are running out of ink it automatically reorder and you get them delivered to your home. 

Overall this is an HP printer and they are reliable. It does the job well, quiet, fast and it’s cost efficient to maintain. It is easy to use and set up. This printer is 60% made of recyclable plastic. It orders inks automatically if you subscribed to the program and you can recycle the used ink cartridges for free. Review_Title: Great economical printer for the home office
Review_Content:
The HP DeskJet 4255e All-in-One Printer is a pretty good printer for the price and it is really tuned to getting office documents printed quickly and easily. 

Design and Build Quality 

The HP DeskJet 4255e is a pretty good looking printer, and it’s small for a printer that also includes a sheetfeeder for the scanner. The printer's build quality is solid, with a sturdy plastic body that feels durable although the plastic seems somewhat textured and that can affect cleaning. The document feeder holds about 35 pages and that’s huge for copying and scanning. 

One thing that’s really strange about this printer is the fairly tiny access door, which is used to change out ink cartridges, is in the bottom front versus a lift up on top. I’m not used to that and I predict that one day clearing paper jams will be fairly tedious or will cause me to hire someone with little fingers and hands to unclog. 

Setup and Connectivity 

Setting up the printer is fairly fast as long as you’re willing to use the HP Smart app. It walks you through the setup of the printer. The setup took about 5 minutes to finish for me on a Pixel phone. If you add printer on the newest MacOS or WindowsOS systems, it will recognize the printer right away and get you started printing. For me, I was up and running in less than 10 minutes. Super benefit. 


Printing and Scanning Performance 

I thought the printing performance was just fine for home use and small business as a non-primary printer. It gets print speeds of up to 8.5 pages per minute (ppm) in black and 5.5 ppm in color, which is adequate for one off print jobs. It can spool using the HP software, but this is not really fast enough to be an enterprise printer.  

The print quality is impressive for basic color documents like recipes, forms, and travel documents, producing sharp text and vibrant colors. Scanning was fairly efficient due to the multi-page document handling. However, it doesn't seem to have duplex scanning, meaning manually flipping pages for two-sided documents. The scan quality is suitable for general use, capturing sufficient detail for documents and simple images. I scanned a photo with the flatbed scanner which was servicable but not really great for production workflows. 

Ink Efficiency and Cost 

You get three months of HP Instant Ink service with HP+. This program is designed to deliver ink cartridges to your door before you run out, based on your usage patterns, which can significantly reduce ink costs. After the initial three months, a subscription fee applies based on what amount of printing you expect to use, you pay per page so if the ink dries out, you just ask HP to fix it for you and they’ll send you another cart. I’m not a fan of subscriptions but it’s worth it to try it out because three free months of printing! The printer uses yet another new print cartridge: HP 67 ink cartridges, available in standard, XL, and XXL sizes to hopefully save you some money when you purchase carts outright . 

Conclusion 

The HP DeskJet 4255e All-in-One Printer is a really economical home use printer. It’s compact , easy, and efficient. The overall value, makes it a worthwhile purchase for a no nonsense color inkjet printer.

Review_Content:

Let's start with its sleek and compact design. The printer's minimalistic appearance blends seamlessly into any workspace, saving valuable desk space. Its small footprint is ideal for those working in confined areas or aiming for a clutter-free environment. The build quality is impressive, giving it a sturdy feel that ensures durability over time.

Setting up the DeskJet 4255e is a breeze, thanks to HP's user-friendly installation process. Within minutes, I was able to connect it to both my computer and mobile devices effortlessly. The printer's functionality as an all-in-one device is a major selling point. Along with high-quality printing, the DeskJet 4255e integrates scanning and copying functionalities flawlessly. When it comes to printing quality, the DeskJet 4255e delivers exceptional results. Another notable feature of the DeskJet 4255e is its commitment to environmental sustainability. The printer is ENERGY STAR® certified, which means it operates efficiently, conserving energy. This program ensures that ink cartridges are automatically delivered to your doorstep before you run out, reducing waste and saving money in the long run.

One aspect that impressed me the most about the DeskJet 4255e is its compatibility with various printing apps. I must also mention the exceptional customer support provided by HP. Their responsive and knowledgeable team promptly addresses any concerns or questions, ensuring a smooth and hassle-free experience.

In conclusion, the HP DeskJet 4255e All-in-One Printer is the ultimate printing solution for both personal and professional needs. Its commitment to sustainability and excellent customer support further enhances its appeal. I highly recommend the DeskJet 4255e to anyone seeking a reliable, efficient, and advanced all-in-one printer that delivers exceptional results.

Review_Title: Affordable full featured color inkjet printer
Review_Content:
The HP DeskJet 4255e Wireless All-in-One Color Printer comes with 3 months of free Instant Ink Included with the HP+ subscription for instant ink.  It’s a great concept if you print a lot of pages per month, a very convenient feature where the HP software will let them know when you’re running low on ink and will automatically ship you the cartridge that needs replacement.  It’s a convenient way to get ink cartridges without lifting a finger.  A family member has last year’s 4155e model which is very similar.  Since he didn’t think he’d be printing that much, he opted out of the HP+ subscription and ended up buying cheaper non-HP cartridges which were not recognized by his printer.  As it turns out it is in the HP documentation that you must use authentic HP cartridges for best performance and reliability.

In terms of unboxing and setup, it’s very straight forward.  Despite its affordable sub $100 price, this is not a basic printer by any means, as it is an all-in-one printer that includes a scanner and automatic document feeder (no FAX). Setup wise, I already had HP Smart software downloaded and installed from having other HP printers connected, but if you don't already have it, expect the download and install to take a while in Windows.  You can also scan the QR code with your phone to download the iOS or Android App that you can use to setup, print and even scan from your phone.  The print speed is reasonable in black up to 8.5ppm, and I timed it at about 5 ppm in color. If you want faster, you’ll have to spend much more and get a Laser printer. I would recommend tweaking the settings to a lower dpi/resolution/quality to speed up printing and conserve ink, unless you're printing pictures on photo paper at 1200x1200dpi. 

It has good connectivity options - I tested USB, WiFi, Apple AirPrint, though No Bluetooth and no memory card reader. Also compatible with most modern Operating systems and mobile devices.  I use multiple Windows 10/11 PCs, Chrome books, Android tablets and phones and an iPad, all printed and scanned flawlessly. If you’re looking for a budget, solid All-in-one printer from the #1 printer company, this HP DeskJet 4255e is a great reliable choice, but the HP branded ink cartridges will cost more than the printer overall in the long run.

Review_Content:
The HP4200e series is HP’s new line of printers. HP being the pioneer in inkjet technology, it comes to no surprise that HP often comes uo with newer models every year. But truth be told, inkjet printers have been around for several decades and one would wonder why should one consider this model.

First, is that the HP 4200e series is very compact. It has a modern looking (with curves) design which is a step away from the boxy designs such as the HP 8030 series it had prior to this release. To further make it a compact printer, HP has designed the back sheet feeder to be foldable as well as the front paper tray so that over all the footprint of this printer is compact as much as possible. There is a downside to this unfortunately as the back sheet feeder can accommodate only up to 60 pages I believe and as compared to up to 150 pages with other models. But do note that the HP4200e series is aimed at home and student users which in my opinion is sufficient for most uses.

One thing I like about this printer is that its scanner has an automated sheet feeder. For some this may not be that important and that a flatbed scanner would suffice, but for me an automatic sheet feeder is crucial as I convert a lot of documents into PDF format. But for those who don’t do a lot of scanning HP also a model without an automatic sheet feeder. And being a printer intended for general home use, this printer no longer has fax functions.

And like most printers, this printer is wi-fi enabled. And though you can still connect this printer via USB cable, it is no longer encouraged by HP as can be seen that the USB port is covered with tape. But the main advantage of having wi-fi is that this printer is HP Instant Ink. But unlike other printer brands, HP actually sends you the ink cartridges. Other brands just give you an alert when ink is low and you have to pick it up yourself.

And lastly, since this printer is intended for home and student use, printer speed is not quite fast at 8.5 ppm. I would have wished this was faster but other than that, this is a fine multi function printer. I would highly recommend this.

Review_Content:
This HP all in-one printer is a good choice for home and/or small business printing needs.

What I like about the printer: 
It's a quick and easy setup. Plug the cord in after removing all packing and tape, download the app and follow the directions. 
Connecting to WiFi is a breeze, it automatically connects. 
Updates are also automatic.
The printer runs smoothly and quietly in print, copy and scan mode. 
It is fast and the prints are clear. 
The automatic feed is an awesome feature for making copies.
Mobile app works great and allows for printing anywhere, anytime.
Can send print jobs to the printer while away from home and, if setup in the app, it will hold the print job until it detects you are near.
Detects ink levels, and with a subscription to Instant Ink, ink will arrive before you run out.
Recycle ink cartridges program.
 
   

What I didn't like:
App on computer didn't run smoothly like the mobile app did. Bit of a headache until it finally recognized the computer had completed setup.
I did receive a message on Windows app that the HP site was down for maintenance, but the mobile app was working just fine.
I'm not a fan of the tri-color ink cartridges preferring individual cartridges for each color. I have never run out of the three colors at the same time. If there were one thing I would change on this printer that would be it.
No automatic two sided printing. I rarely use it, but it is nice to have when needed.Two sided printing can be done manually though.

The dislikes/problems are minor to me, but I include them in case they are important to others.

Review_Content:
This HP wireless printer stands out as an exemplary model for both home and office use, reflecting HP's reputation as America's most trusted printer brand. Its compact design and multifunction capabilities make it a versatile choice, especially for those looking to maximize their productivity without consuming too much space. With the capability to print, scan, and copy, this printer is equipped with an automatic document feeder (ADF) that holds up to 35 pages, facilitating the easy handling of multi-page documents—a feature that significantly boosts efficiency.

The setup benefits from the HP+ system, which does require an HP account and continuous internet so keep that in mind. Choosing HP+ during the setup activates several benefits, including the exclusive use of Original HP Ink cartridges. This could be a double-edged sword for those who prefer third-party cheaper options, but HP argues this ensures optimum printer performance throughout its lifespan. The printer’s ink subscription service, Instant Ink, promises up to 50% savings on ink, which is automatically delivered to your door. This service not only offers convenience and cost savings but also allows flexibility with the option to modify or cancel subscriptions without additional fees.

On the technical side, the print quality great, with resolutions up to 1200 x 1200 rendered dpi for black and white, and up to 4800 x 1200 optimized dpi for color prints. Such high resolutions ensure sharp text and vibrant colors, suitable for a variety of documents and images. Scanning and copying also boast high resolutions, making this printer a solid choice for precise document reproduction.

Wireless connectivity is a standout feature, supporting various mobile printing options like Apple AirPrint, Google’s Chrome OS, and Mopria, along with HP’s own mobile app. This printer’s built-in Wi-Fi is engineered for reliability, capable of reconnecting automatically if the connection drops, ensuring a smooth and continuous workflow.

My wife, who uses this printer in her home office, appreciates its quiet operation and the ADF's efficiency for managing her daily tasks of scanning and copying multi-page contracts and documents. She finds the LCD ICON display intuitive and easy to navigate, which complements her multitasking environment by streamlining her operations.

Lastly, HP's commitment to sustainability is evident in this model, which is made from at least 60% recycled plastic. Additionally, the company’s proactive approach to forest conservation and recycling program for used cartridges adds a level of corporate responsibility that enhances the overall value of this printer.

In conclusion, this HP wireless printer is a highly recommended solution for anyone seeking a reliable, high-quality printer that combines functionality with sustainability, all managed through the easiest-to-use print app available. It’s an ideal choice for home offices, like my wife’s, providing all the necessary tools to streamline office tasks efficiently and effectively.

Review_Content:
This is a great little printing solution for most home needs.  It doesn’t do super high end photo resolutions, or print super lighting fast, but it gets the job done.

+++ INSTALLATION +++

	Setup is straightforward. If you have used a printer in the last 5 years or so you should know what to expect. You connect this to your Wi-Fi, and you are up and running within minutes. We got this so my kids had something at home to use to print out schoolwork. Since it is on our network, they are all able to print to this from their laptops, and their other devices. I needed to print out an email for one of my sons and I was able to select the printer on my phone and print to it with no issues.

+++FEATURES / PERFORMANCE+++

	The auto feeder is nice for when we need to scan documents to email out to teachers or store them on the computer. Text looks good on here as well as clipart in color. I probably wouldn’t be using this to print out photos to frame, but for just about anything else this will be more than adequate. 
	You are only allowed to use official HP branded ink on here, and they offer up a subscription to get ink refills mailed to you. I am not quite sure we will be using it enough to require the subscription, but if you are using it quite a bit then that might be an easy route to go to get the ink replenished. 

+++CONCLUSION+++

	For most day-to-day use scenarios this printer is more than enough. If you require a printer that also prints out high quality photos, then you might find something a bit better out there. For general and school use this is great.

Review_Title: Easy setup, perfect for simple home usage
Review_Content:
I've had a great experience with the HP - DeskJet 4255e.  My previous printer just stopped working a few months back and this is a welcome replacement.  I really only have pros.  For me, this is for simple home use.  So printing documents that I might need to sign or drawing pages for my kids.  My son made a collage of Kobe Bryant the other day and printed it some the iPad.  For what I'd expect from a printer in this price range and capabilities, the quality is good in both black and white and color.

Set up was easy.  You download the app, plug it in and put in the provided ink cartridges.  I signed in because my previous printer was an HP, and I already had an account.  Click add a printed and follow the prompts.  I put in the Wi-Fi info and it completed setup.  It prints a test page that you also put on the scanner bed and push the copy button to calibrate the machine.  Ready to go.  For me, 3 Minutes from sign in to calibrated.

Since then, I mentioned the collage that my son did, but I've printed some documents in black and white and some documents with a little color, like logos and some colored font.  Like I mentioned, for the cost and specs for these simple around the home things, it's great.  Scanning is also great.  I'm a little old school in that I prefer to use a machine to scan because I find that they do better than the app-based ones.  The image pops up in the app and you can save it from there.

Overall, this is great for simple home usage.  If you print a lot and speed and high quality for things like images are very important, then you might want a machine with some higher capabilities.  For printing documents, coloring pages and images for fun, I would highly recommend the HP - DeskJet 4255e.

Review_Content:
Printers have come a long way in the recent past.  I recall waiting for a the printer to "warm up" for what seemed like an eternity.  This is not the case anymore.  This printers boils down into 3 areas of focus which either need improvement or are out of this park in terms of performance: build, response rate, and long term cost.

The build of this printer is a little on the frail side, I understand that printers are everchanging and there needs to be gives and takes but from what I am experiencing this build is a tad thin or flimsy side.  When setting it up I was very hesitant that I was going to crack some of the trays or the outer shell.  With that said, nothing ever broke but it does have a "too thin" feel to it.  On the benefit side it is light weight... so, a give for a take.

On the response rate side, it seems like this printer is ready to go on a moments notice, even for a Deskjet.  And, with paired with the companion app, items can easily be printed without the rigmarole of copy and pasting.  The wifi connection of this item also adds the the speed of click to print time, no need to get onto a hard-wired device to print anymore either.  All of these items as described, although only reduce seconds to the printing experience do in fact speed up the process ten fold.

Lastly, cost always comes to mind.  Firstly, this printer is made of 60% recycled materials, which is technically a cost savings to the planet, but I digress.  The ink usage efficiency is top notch, when printing color or B&W.  It is noted that a 50% ink savings can be attained when using HP's ink subscription service too.  Pairing all of this with its energy savings mode is a recipe to max savings across many different spectrums. 

All in all, if you are looking for a light weight, eco-friendly, efficient printer that has a quick "click to print" speed, then this is a great option for you.

Review_Content:
The HP Deskjet 4255e wireless all in one printer does a great job with a compact footprint.  The printer is fairly easy to set-up but does require the use of the HP smart app.  I already own a HP laser jet printer so adding this printer to the app took a few minutes.  Once added the printer goes through the set up process where it prints an alignment sheet which is then scanned to ensure optimal printing.  Once this was all done I was able to print an email and a picture from my phone wirelessly without any issues.

This printer was an add on to my office laser jet printer since the kids need a color option for school assignments.  The printer features an input tray capable of holding 60 sheets of paper as well as an automatic document feeder that can hold 35 sheets of paper which makes scanning or copying multiple documents easy. The printer did include a free 3 month trial to HP instant ink which is essentially a service by HP which ensures that you are auto shipped ink before you run out. This is a great service because you will never be running around to random stores looking for ink cartridges at 9pm because your kids have to print something to take to school the next morning.  Using the HP smart app allows you to get the most out of the printer however it does have a small LCD screen on the front which allows you to see some useful information such as ink levels, error codes, Wi-Fi status, number of copies and finally any issue with the paper such as paper jams.

Simply put the HP Deskjet 4255e was wasy to set up and use out of the box and I hope to be using it for a few years.

Review_Title: A Decent Printer for Home Use
Review_Content:
The DeskJet 4255e is an all in one print/copy/scan machine.  It has a traditional design of a rear paper feeder as well as a flatbed scanner with automatic feeder.  It does not have fax capability.  It accepts two different cartridges; a black ink and a multi-color ink cartridge that are very small.  They are small by design as HP anticipates that you will use this printer occasionally.  But also, HP is pushing their HP+ ink delivery service that calculates your ink usage and charges you an amount based on how often you use ink.  This is offered on most of their printers, so I won’t talk about that so much.  But again, the cartridges are small and can be used relatively quickly.  I printed a couple of test pages and one document with a photo that took 1/8th of the page, and I've already used 1/5th of the color ink.  That is fast.

Set up is relatively simple.  It comes with a quick start guide to walk you through the WiFi connection process, but what you’ll need mainly is the HP Smart App, either on your Windows PC, iOS or Android.  The 4255e will print a set of instructions on how to connect your printer to your network for each OS type.  Once you’re connected to the network, HP will then ask you to opt-in on HP Smart Printing as well as offer you 3 free months of ink delivery service.  If you decline both, you’ve still a working printer and you are not required to have either service.  After I was done following the instructions (holding the WiFi and cancel buttons for a few seconds puts the printer into WiFi setup mode), the printer was now on my home network for other devices to find.

As far as print quality, I find it to be nominal for an inkjet printer.  You can change print quality to adjust speed as well as ink usage.  The better the quality, the more ink is used.  I feel that most can get by using the Fast/Economical setting to crank out many documents and save ink.  Normal and photo settings will look nicer, but use more ink.  You can set these defaults in the HP app.

The last cool thing worth mentioning is HP Smart Printing, which allows you to print from any device, even if you’re not on the same network.  The  4255e will take advantage of its connection to your WiFi and make itself available to you, no matter where you may be.  Now it might be a strange use-case for many considering this printer will probably be used at home, but the benefit is that all your devices don’t have to be connected to the network.  You just simply log into your HP Smart account and you will gain access to the 4255e.

What you won’t find on this printer is automatic duplex printing. Luckily,  there is a manual rendition of it  which requires you to take a printed page and re-feed it back into the sheet hopper to print on the back.  I can see this being okay for maybe 2-3 pages, but anything more than that can incur a bit of human interaction.

Overall, I like what HP did here with the DeskJet 4255e.  It’s definitely not the fanciest printer as reflected by its affordability, but it does bring the essential features needed at home.  This is most definitely an at-home use printer.  We’re not exactly breaking any barriers with 8.5 ppm black/5.5 ppm color, and not to mention the small 60 sheet capacity.  This is, in fact, marketed as a monthly-use printer.  An “every now and then” kind of printer.  And maybe that’s all you really need.

Review_Content:
The HP DeskJet 4255e is a budget-friendly, all-in-one printer with a range of useful features, making it ideal for average PC users. Its affordable price, easy setup via the HP Smart app, and compact design are significant advantages. The printer supports wireless connectivity, allowing printing from various devices, and includes an HP Instant Ink subscription option to manage ink costs efficiently. The print quality for text documents is decent, and mobile printing is convenient.

However, the printer has some drawbacks. The print speed is relatively slow, and the photo printing quality is average. It lacks automatic duplex printing and an Ethernet port. It can be noisy during operation. The paper handling capacity is limited, with a 60-sheet input tray and a 25-sheet output tray. The automatic document feeder (ADF) holds up to 35 sheets, which is useful but may struggle with thicker or irregular-sized documents.

Overall, the HP DeskJet 4255e offers good value for money for light to moderate use, especially with the HP Instant Ink program, but it may not be suitable for heavy-duty printing needs.

Review_Content:
Unboxing the HP DeskJet 4255e All-in-One Printer was a pleasant experience. The packaging was minimal but secure, and the printer was easy to extract from the box. Right away, the compact and sleek design caught my eye. With its clean lines and modern aesthetic, this printer looks good enough to sit out in any home or office setting without being an eyesore.

Setting up the DeskJet 4255e was refreshingly straightforward. The included setup guide was clear and easy to follow. Within minutes, the printer was connected to my Wi-Fi network and ready to go. The touchscreen display is intuitive and made navigating through the initial setup a breeze, even for those who aren't particularly tech-savvy.

The HP Smart app is a highlight of the DeskJet 4255e. Available for both iOS and Android, the app makes mobile printing and scanning incredibly easy. The user interface is intuitive, with a variety of features like mobile faxing and printer status monitoring. I particularly appreciated the seamless integration with cloud storage services, allowing me to print documents directly from Google Drive and Dropbox.

When it comes to printing speed, the DeskJet 4255e holds its own. It’s not the fastest printer on the market, but for its size and price, it performs admirably. Text documents print quickly and clearly, with sharp, legible fonts. Photo printing is equally impressive, with vibrant colors and fine details, making it suitable for printing everything from professional documents to family photos.

The HP DeskJet 4255e is a cost-effective choice, especially when paired with HP's Instant Ink subscription service. This service can save users up to 50% on ink costs, with the added convenience of automatic cartridge replacements. This means you’ll never run out of ink unexpectedly, which is a huge plus for those with regular printing needs. The printer itself is also fairly efficient, making good use of each cartridge and keeping operating costs relatively low.

Overall, the HP DeskJet 4255e All-in-One Printer is a fantastic option for anyone in need of a reliable, versatile printer. Its sleek design, easy setup, and strong performance make it a standout in its price range. The added benefits of the HP Smart app and cost-effective ink options further enhance its appeal. Whether you're printing important work documents or cherished family photos, the DeskJet 4255e delivers quality results with minimal hassle. For those looking for an all-in-one solution that combines style, functionality, and affordability, this printer is a top contender.
