Review_Title: Stay away from the ink subscription
Review_Content: The printer itself is okay. Nothing special. But I made the mistake of subscribing to their ink cartridge program. Big mistake. You pay so much a month depending on how many pages you print. If you sign up for 10 pages a month @$2 a month and go over that amount, you're charged $1 per page. Of course the amount of unused pages doesn't carry over to the next month, so if you print zero for three months-- and are charged $6, and the next month print 20 pages, you'll be charged $10 for the extra pages!  Worst of all, if you unsubscribe, the printer won't work on the cartridges you've already paid for!  You're forced to continue "subscribing." Beware. Just buy ink from Amazon.

Review_Title: Sent back: Dynamic Security chip on printer ink
Review_Content: This printer might seem like a good deal at first, but it’s really just a ploy to lock you into buying expensive ink from HP.I bought this to replace my HP  4255e after its printhead failed, and even the replacement head didn’t work. This printer cost me about $50 less than that replacement head alone, so I thought I was getting a bargain.The setup was straightforward, and it connected to my network without any issues. However, I’m uneasy about how HP connects to the printer over the internet—who knows what data they’re collecting?One glaring flaw is the lack of automatic two-sided printing. Instead, you have to manually reload the paper to print on the other side, following on-screen prompts. It’s an annoying step back from the fully automated feature I had before.The switch to a single color cartridge is a step backward, too. It’s more convenient, but with separate cartridges, you could at least use up each color fully before replacing it. Now, you’re throwing money away when one color runs out.The so-called “free” 6-month trial of HP’s Instant Ink (Dynamic Security chip on printer ink ) program is just a sneaky way to milk more money out of you. It’s not really an ink subscription; it’s a deal where you pay for the number of pages you print each month, regardless of how much ink you actually use. Even if you print just one word on a page, it counts towards your limit. If you cancel the program, any ink they’ve already sent becomes useless, forcing you to buy their overpriced cartridges. I canceled it and switched to aftermarket ink, which works just as well for half the price.Print quality is also a letdown. It’s nowhere near the standard of my old 8610, though it’s adequate for basic home printing. Forget about using it for anything professional or for printing barcodes—scan codes often don’t work on the first try. I printed show tickets, and the usher had to scan them several times to get them to work. The same issue happens with UPC-style codes, though QR codes fare a little better.Bottom line: I would never buy this printer again. After this experience, I’m done with HP printers altogether.

I recently purchased the HP DeskJet 2820e multifunction printer hoping to have an affordable and convenient home printing solution. However, after using it for a while, I'm pretty disappointed and regret the purchase. While the printer is fine in terms of features (printing, scanning, copying, and Wi-Fi), the running costs are ridiculously high. The cartridges are extremely expensive and seem to run out much faster than expected. After doing the math, I found that the price per page is more expensive than getting it printed at a local store! For anyone who prints regularly, this is a complete rip-off. The included HP Instant Ink may sound like a good deal at first, but after the free period ends, it becomes another ongoing expense. For a budget printer, the cost of ink completely undermines the supposed savings. I wouldn't recommend this printer to anyone who values ​​long-term cost efficiency. It may work for occasional users, but if you only print moderately, it's cheaper and less stressful to go to the print shop. Save yourself the hassle and look for an alternative.
For this money everything is good - whoever prints more should go up a level

Review_Title: HP Printers - The More Time Passes, The Less They Do
Review_Content: I wanted to replace an old HP whose Flash-based software is no longer supported by HP itself, so I got this printer. In my case I noticed scans without OCR even though I installed both HP Smart and HP scanner (500 MB more to get the same result). Also all scans were crooked in the same way (incorrect or absent calibration of the scanning light...). The scans were worse than the old (similar) printer and eliminated all the colored shades, except red and black. Basically they were scans with totally incorrect exposure, perhaps oriented to photocopies of texts but to be thrown away for any image. Finally we are at only 300 dpi, when the model (as I said similar) reached 1200 Dpi 15 years ago. I tried to print an altimetric map and it missed all the grays of the PDF, printing only the lines. Look at the current printer (NEW) in comparison with another model (OLD). Note: the dentist's background is a shade of blue, so you decide..Is there anything else to say? Well... returned without any regrets.

Review_Title: HP Deskjet 4255e...Easy set up but connect mobile device first....
Review_Content: I had to replace my very old Canon Pixma and I couldn't pass up this deal especially with the 3 month Free Ink replacement.I have a 2017 MacAir and once I went to 123.hp.com to connect the printer to my Mac I received a "pop-up" stating I needed Big Sur Upgrade in order to proceed & connect this printer but my Mac is not compatible with that program. After 3 hours of wasted time condensing, deleting files, etc. I decided to just connect my mobile device since everything I would possibly use the printer for was also on my cell as well.  It took MAYBE 10 minutes at the most to connect via 123.hp.com and I was also able to receive the trial ink cartridges for 3 months. After finally testing the printer and loving it I took a break from my phone, etc to give my eyes a break.  Once I had a clear head I remembered System Preferences has a "Printer/Scanner" icon.  I went back to my Mac, clicked on that (if this is your first printer remember to turn off any Firewalls FIRST otherwise you will not be able to connect the printer. You can turn it back on once the Printer is in your system) and after adding the HP Deskjet 4255e with location (my home address), etc I had the printer connected and working with my Mac within a few minutes.That is everything in a nutshell and I hope this review helps anybody else in the future with their setup.You will definitely LOVE this Printer and the ease of operating it.

Review_Content: Ill make it short and sweet. Ive had this printer for about 6 months. In terms of functionality, this printer has worked really well for me. Never had any issues with connectivity or even the hp printer software. The only issue (someone else used this term well), this printer is not yours after you buy it. It is essentially a rental. If you do not have a currently active instant ink subscription service going, hp software will not allow you to print anything. Now, the service is relatively inexpensive. About $6 or $7 a month and Ive never been in a spot where I am out of ink. But for those of us who only print a few pages a couple of days out if the month, this will not be the best printer to get. Ive had a payment not go through once due to me getting a new debit card and it took me a good 20 minutes to get it up and going again after changing my payment info. Doesn’t matter how many pages you printed, how much ink you have used. You’re giving them $6 and swapping out your hardly used ink carts for new ones or else you will not be allowed to use the printer. Pretty shady if you ask me and im not comfortable with the way they can remotely prevent you from using your printer that you already purchased. Ill be continuing to use mine until i can eventually afford something that is better fit for less frequent printing/cart replacements but if you’re reading this. Id recommend avoiding any hp printer that requires you to have an instant ink subscription.
Aggregation_Flag: Style: New Version

Review_Content: As someone who frequently prints for personal projects and small business needs, I was on the hunt for an all-in-one printer that wouldn't break the bank. I’d give this printer a solid B+ for ease of setup on my iPhone 15 and MacBook Air. Sure, I ran into a few bumps along the way, but after a couple of tries and about 30 minutes, I finally got it up and running.However, as someone with multiple health challenges, I found swapping out the ink cartridges to be a bit of a struggle. I’ve owned several HP printers over the years, and with most of them, you could easily lift the scanner bed to install the cartridges. But with the HP4255e, there’s a tight front flap near the paper exit that makes it tricky. If you don’t get the cartridge in just the right spot, it can take a bit of wrestling to get it seated correctly. I really wish it had a top-loading option instead.Another hiccup was the printing delay. There were times when I’d hit “print” on both my phone and laptop, only to wait around three minutes before hearing the printer start to pull the paper in, followed by another 90 seconds of silence. A few times, it actually finished printing about 15 minutes after I first hit “print,” but more often than not, it just stalled out. I tried everything I could think of—uninstalling and reinstalling the HP Smart app on all my devices, unplugging the printer, and even going through tech support for over an hour. Unfortunately, even with their guidance, the inconsistencies persisted. It wasn’t until after my call with them that I realized I should try printing directly through the Smart App on my phone, and that finally worked for me. So, I’m left unable to print from my laptop, which is a bit frustrating.Oh, and I must admit, I was a bit disappointed to discover there’s no automatic duplex printing. That’s more of a personal preference, but it did catch me off guard. Honestly, I’d only recommend this printer to someone who prints infrequently and is okay with using the app.On a positive note, when it does print, the quality is beautiful! However, I’m puzzled as to how I went through almost half of my color ink cartridge in less than 24 hours after getting the machine. I only printed about 10 pages, mostly black and white with just a few colored elements. Overall, it’s a mixed bag for me!
Aggregation_Flag: Style: New Version

Orginal_Title: Muy recomendable con el servicio HP Instant Ink

Review_Content: The printer itself does its job well, it works well even with a single cartridge and this is an appreciated plus. There are 2 things that really need to be improved: - the app that they make you download for the additional functions, such as scan, fax, etc. that the printer does not have buttons (the only problem is that you cannot scan both sides of the same sheet) because it is very slow, it often blocks, in short very long waits.... Then the ink level is never clear.. Failed. The only thing that I find useful is the function of printing from another place far from the printer in real time, such as home - office. - the instant link service. The possibility of testing the service for 3 months for free is excellent, to actually verify its convenience. Failed the shipping service that arrives from Germany, in practice you have to keep the printer always on so by monitoring the ink level they will ship it to you before it runs out in theory, in practice it runs out and you are still waiting for delivery, this also applies to the welcome kit. Also 2 out of 3 cartridges arrived defective and unusable, leaving you in an uncomfortable situation again. The cartridge disposal service is not clear and it's a shame. Then the printer does not print well if you exceed the number of pages purchased in the package, even if maybe the ink is there. We will evaluate whether not to continue with this service after the free period and see what the performance is with the cartridges purchased in the store, certainly the printer is cheap but the cartridges in the long run less so 😅😅

Review_Content: This was very difficult to set up using the instructions included, the first attempt was to persuade me to part with money for a driver updater and nothing to do with the printer.  Eventually managed to pick our way through the confusing and unhelpful instructions on-screen.  Once that was done, still awkward to get it to print and have to go through a final screen to print which was unnecessary.  However, the printer kept cutting out and going off.  Discovered this yesterday - the power lead is very loose connecting to the printer body and kept falling out or too loose for power.  The printer itself is elegant, a nice white colour, the printing is quicker than Canon (don't ever be tempted to buy a Canon) and above all very quiet.  The only problem is that the paper catcher is inadequate and there is a piece of plastic sticking out the base at the front which serves no purpose.  The power on light is also white which is a bit hard to see.  The problem with the power lead was reported to Amazon and they are replacing the machine the next day.  Having said all of the above, in my experience of printers in this price range, I would recommend this one.

Review_Title: Simple 2 in 1 printer for a small office.
Review_Content: Lovely pri ter that is working well in a back office.

The HP Deskjet 2852e is the same printer as the Deskjet 2855e which is currently retailing on BestBuy %26 Amazon for $85. I believe the 2852e is a model specific to be sold by Wal Mart only and for its $54 price, it's a great value for money printer. I would recommend this to people that expect to do minimal or occasional printing %26 scanning at home and would be okay with using HP Ink Cartridges Only as you essentially have to enroll in HP's Instant Ink Program for its core functionality (the cheapest plan starts at $1.50 a month) . If you plan on using 3rd Party Ink Providers, I would recommend you look at Brother or Canon Printers instead (those are what I use at my office and those brands work better with 3rd party ink). Setup was very easy with the HP Smart App on my PC and iPhone. This comes built-in with Apple AirPrint which is very convenient for those of you that need to print something directly from your iPhone or iPad. Finally, it's relatively compact and small so that's another plus!
